    "**What does 'shape' mean?**\n",
    "\n",
    "`df.shape` returns a tuple `(rows, columns)`. For example, `(200, 15)` means the dataset has 200 rows (records/customers) and 15 columns (features/attributes). This is the most fundamental piece of information about a dataset's size.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What each column represents:**\n",
    "- `User ID`: A unique identifier assigned to each customer. Not useful for modeling - identifiers have no predictive power.\n",
    "- `Area code`: The area code of the customer's residence. A proxy for geographic location.\n",
    "- `Location`: The neighborhood and city where the customer lives.\n",
    "- `Gender`: The customer's gender (Male/Female).\n",
    "- `YOB`: Year of Birth. We will transform this into Age.\n",
    "- `Marital Status`: Customer's marital status (Single/Married/Divorced).\n",
    "- `Activity`: Career status - whether the customer is a Student or Professional.\n",
    "- `Budget`: The budget level the customer is willing to spend (1-5 scale).\n",
    "- `Cuisines`: The type of cuisine the customer prefers (Japanese, Indian, French, etc.).\n",
    "- `Alcohol`: How frequently the customer consumes alcohol (Never/Often/Socially).\n",
    "- `Smoker`: Whether the customer smokes (Never/Often/Socially).\n",
    "- `Food Rating`: Rating given specifically for food quality.\n",
    "- `Service Rating`: Rating given specifically for service quality.\n",
    "- `Overall Rating`: The combined overall rating. This is our **target variable** for prediction.\n",
    "- `Often A S`: Indicates frequency status - appears to be related to smoking/alcohol habits.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
