    "## 4. Understanding the Dataset Structure\n",
    "\n",
    "Before cleaning or modeling, we need to deeply understand what kind of data we have. This involves examining data types, identifying missing values, and understanding the distribution of values in each column.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why Do Data Types Matter in Modeling?\n",
    "\n",
    "Machine learning algorithms are fundamentally mathematical operations. They work on numbers, not text. If a column that should be numeric (e.g., `Budget` with values 1-5) is stored as a string (object type), mathematical operations like computing the mean will fail or produce wrong results. Identifying and correcting data types is a critical step.\n",
    "\n",
    "### What Happens if a Numeric Column is Treated as Object?\n",
    "\n",
    "If the `Budget` column is stored as an object type:\n",
    "- `df['Budget'].mean()` will raise a `TypeError`.\n",
    "- The column cannot be used directly in any mathematical model.\n",
    "- Statistical summaries will be incomplete.\n",
    "- Sorting will be lexicographic (1, 10, 2, 3) instead of numeric (1, 2, 3, 10)."
   ]
