    "### 5.2 Handling Missing Values\n",
    "\n",
    "Even if this dataset has few or no missing values, understanding how to handle them is critical for your career. Here is the complete framework:\n",
    "\n",
    "**Strategy 1 - Drop rows:** Only acceptable if the missing percentage is very small (less than 2%) and the dataset is large. Dropping rows when the dataset is small loses valuable information.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Strategy 2 - Imputation:** Filling in missing values with a calculated value.\n",
    "- **Mean imputation** (for numerical columns): Replace missing values with the column's average. Use when the data is normally distributed (symmetric bell curve). The danger is that if there are extreme outliers, the mean is pulled away from the center, making imputation inaccurate.\n",
    "- **Median imputation** (for numerical columns): Replace missing values with the column's median. Use when the data is skewed (not symmetric). The median is not affected by extreme outliers, making it more robust.\n",
    "- **Mode imputation** (for categorical columns): Replace missing values with the most frequently occurring value. This is the only reasonable option for text/category data.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What happens if we impute incorrectly?** We introduce bias. For instance, if 30% of 'Age' values are missing and we impute all with the mean, we are essentially inventing data for 30% of our dataset. This can make the model think age has much less variability than it actually does, leading to underestimation of age's predictive power.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Real-world impact of skipping imputation:** A production model receiving records with missing values will either crash or produce wildly wrong predictions, leading to business losses and user distrust."
   ]
