    "### 5.4 Fixing Inconsistent Categorical Data\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why does categorical consistency matter?**\n",
    "\n",
    "Computers perform exact string matching. The strings `'NY'`, `'ny'`, `'N.Y.'`, and `'New York'` are four completely different values to Python. If your Location column has some entries as `'St. George,ny'` and others as `'St. George,NY'`, these will be treated as two different locations, doubling the number of apparent categories and distorting any analysis grouped by location.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is called **data inconsistency** and it is extremely common in real-world datasets collected from multiple sources or entered manually by different people.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What happens if we skip this step?** Group-by operations will produce incorrect results. For example, `df.groupby('Location')['Overall Rating'].mean()` would show St. George,NY and St. George,ny as two separate groups with incorrect averages, making your analysis wrong."
